-- ‚îÄ‚îÄ Microsoft Power Apps ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$A low-code application development platform from Microsoft that lets users build custom business apps with minimal coding, connected to Dataverse and hundreds of data sources.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Subscription$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free (Developer Plan)$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(1975, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$220,000+ employees (Microsoft Corporation)$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Redmond, Washington, USA$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$, $q$Spanish$q$, $q$French$q$, $q$German$q$, $q$Portuguese$q$, $q$Chinese$q$, $q$Japanese$q$, $q$Korean$q$, $q$Italian$q$, $q$Dutch$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Microsoft Power Apps Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Microsoft Power Apps review covering low-code app building, Dataverse, Premium and pay-as-you-go pricing, and how it compares to other low-code platforms.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Microsoft Power Apps is a low-code application development platform that lets business users and professional developers build custom apps with minimal hand-written code. It became generally available in November 2016 as part of Microsoft's newly formed Power Platform, alongside what was then Microsoft Flow (now Power Automate). Power Apps works by providing a visual, drag-and-drop app designer (canvas apps) alongside a data-first, model-driven app builder (model-driven apps) that generates a full app automatically from an underlying data model in Microsoft Dataverse, Microsoft's proprietary cloud data platform. Apps built in Power Apps can pull from hundreds of standard and premium data connectors, including SharePoint, SQL Server, Excel, Salesforce, and SAP, and can be extended with custom connectors and AI Builder, a feature that adds pre-built AI models (like form processing or object detection) into an app without requiring data science expertise. Power Apps also supports Power Pages, a related capability for building external-facing, low-code websites tied to the same Dataverse backend. Pricing has shifted meaningfully in recent years: Microsoft phased out the older Per App plan (which had been priced around $5 per user per app per month) from its licensing guide in January 2026, leaving two primary paths for most customers. Power Apps Premium is priced at $20 per user per month (billed annually) and gives each licensed user unlimited access to build and run any number of apps and Power Pages sites, including premium connectors, Dataverse, and 500 AI Builder credits per user per month; large-scale enterprise deployments (2,000+ seats) can access reduced volume pricing around $12 per user per month. A Pay-As-You-Go plan charges roughly $10 per active user per app per month, billing only for users who actually open an app in a given month, which suits pilots, seasonal workers, or external vendor access where a full per-user license would be wasteful. A free Power Apps Developer Plan lets individuals build and test apps for learning and prototyping purposes, though it is not intended for production use. Any app built in Power Apps also requires the underlying user to have a Microsoft 365 license, since Power Apps is designed to sit alongside, not replace, an organization's core Microsoft 365 subscription. Power Apps' target audience spans citizen developers (non-technical business users automating a departmental process), IT teams building governed line-of-business apps, and professional developers extending apps with custom code and APIs. Its main competitors are OutSystems, Mendix, Appian, and Salesforce's low-code tools, and its key differentiation is deep integration with the rest of the Power Platform (Power Automate, Power BI, Copilot Studio) and Microsoft 365, plus a shared Dataverse backend that lets apps, automations, and reports all draw from the same governed data model.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'f60ec8fa-b75a-462e-84f1-bc0d2d866e63';

