-- ‚îÄ‚îÄ Microsoft Power Automate ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Microsoft's workflow automation platform for connecting apps, automating repetitive tasks, and running attended or unattended robotic process automation (RPA) bots.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Subscription$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Included with Microsoft 365 (standard connectors); $15/user/month for Premium$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(1975, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$220,000+ employees (Microsoft Corporation)$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Redmond, Washington, USA$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$, $q$Spanish$q$, $q$French$q$, $q$German$q$, $q$Portuguese$q$, $q$Chinese$q$, $q$Japanese$q$, $q$Korean$q$, $q$Italian$q$, $q$Dutch$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Microsoft Power Automate Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Microsoft Power Automate review covering cloud flows, RPA bots, per-user and per-flow pricing, and how it compares to Zapier and UiPath.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Microsoft Power Automate is Microsoft's workflow automation and robotic process automation (RPA) platform, part of the Power Platform alongside Power Apps and Power BI. It launched as Microsoft Flow, first announced in April 2016 with general availability in October 2016, and was rebranded to Power Automate on November 4, 2019 at Microsoft Ignite, a change that also expanded its scope from purely cloud-based workflows to include desktop RPA and virtual agents. Power Automate works through cloud flows (automated, scheduled, or manually triggered workflows connecting cloud apps and services), desktop flows (RPA automations that record and replay actions across desktop and legacy applications), and business process flows (guided, multi-step processes for enforcing a consistent process across a team). Any organization already on Microsoft 365 can build cloud flows using standard connectors, covering commonly used Microsoft apps like Outlook, SharePoint, Teams, OneDrive, Excel, Forms, and Planner, without purchasing a separate Power Automate license. Flows that use premium connectors, such as Salesforce, SAP, or custom connectors to third-party systems, require a separate Power Automate Premium license at $15 per user per month, which also includes unlimited cloud flows, desktop flows in attended mode, 5,000 AI Builder credits, and cloud database/file storage. Unattended RPA, where bots run automatically without a human triggering or supervising each run, requires the Process plan at $150 per bot per month, or a Hosted Process plan at $215 per bot per month that includes Microsoft-hosted infrastructure so the bot doesn't need a dedicated on-premises machine. An alternative Per Flow plan, priced around $500 per month for 5 flows, is available for organizations that want to license specific high-value organizational flows rather than licensing every individual user. Process Mining, an add-on for analyzing and visualizing how existing business processes actually run in practice (as opposed to how they're documented), is available only with the Premium plan for an additional $5,000 per tenant per month, billed annually. Power Automate's target audience ranges from everyday Microsoft 365 users automating personal or team-level tasks (like saving email attachments to OneDrive) to enterprise automation and RPA teams replacing manual, repetitive back-office processes with unattended bots. Its main competitors are Zapier, UiPath, Automation Anywhere, and Make (formerly Integromat), and its key differentiation is native inclusion of basic cloud automation inside every Microsoft 365 subscription, combined with a path to enterprise-grade unattended RPA within the same platform rather than requiring a separate RPA vendor.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '11ea99d1-4f63-4f6b-9533-0e1448c3d8f5';

