-- ‚îÄ‚îÄ Microsoft Power BI ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Microsoft's business intelligence and data visualization platform for building interactive reports and dashboards from data across an organization.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Subscription$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free (Power BI Desktop); $14/user/month for Pro$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(1975, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$220,000+ employees (Microsoft Corporation)$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Redmond, Washington, USA$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$, $q$Spanish$q$, $q$French$q$, $q$German$q$, $q$Portuguese$q$, $q$Chinese$q$, $q$Japanese$q$, $q$Korean$q$, $q$Italian$q$, $q$Dutch$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Microsoft Power BI Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Microsoft Power BI review covering Pro, Premium Per User and Fabric pricing, dashboards, data modeling, and how it compares to Tableau and Looker.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Microsoft Power BI is a business intelligence and data visualization platform that lets organizations build interactive reports and dashboards from data spread across many sources. It began life as Power BI for Office 365, first previewed in July 2013 and unveiled more broadly in September 2013 as an add-on tightly integrated with Excel and SharePoint. The standalone product most people recognize today, including Power BI Desktop, the cloud-based Power BI Service, and Power BI Mobile apps, officially launched on July 24, 2015. Microsoft strengthened its mobile BI capabilities the same year by acquiring Canadian company Datazen in April 2015. Power BI works by connecting to hundreds of data sources, ranging from Excel files and SQL databases to cloud services like Salesforce and Google Analytics, through Power BI Desktop, a free Windows application where users model data, define relationships, and build report visuals using the DAX (Data Analysis Expressions) formula language. Finished reports are then published to the Power BI Service, a cloud platform for sharing dashboards, scheduling data refreshes, and collaborating with colleagues. As of 2026, Power BI is used by over 350,000 organizations worldwide, and Microsoft has shipped more than 1,500 feature updates to the platform since its 2015 launch. Pricing centers on a free Power BI Desktop application for building reports, paired with paid licenses required to share and collaborate on published reports in an organization. Power BI Pro costs $14 per user per month (paid annually), a price increase from $10 that took effect in April 2025, and includes app workspace collaboration, standard refresh rates, and access to the Power BI Service. Power BI Premium Per User (PPU) costs $24 per user per month (up from $20, a roughly 20 percent increase alongside the Pro price change) and adds a much larger dataset size limit of 100 GB (versus Pro's 1 GB), up to 48 daily data refreshes instead of 8, paginated reports, deployment pipelines, and advanced AI features. Beyond per-user licensing, Microsoft also sells capacity-based Premium (P-SKU) licensing for large organizations that need to share reports broadly without every viewer needing an individual Pro license; Microsoft has been gradually steering customers from traditional Premium capacity toward its newer Fabric capacity SKUs at renewal, positioning Fabric as the long-term successor for large-scale analytics workloads. Power BI's target audience spans business analysts and data teams building reports, up through IT and data platform teams managing enterprise-wide dashboards and governed datasets, and it is especially popular among organizations already invested in the Microsoft 365 and Azure ecosystem. Its main competitors are Tableau, Google Looker, and Qlik Sense, and its key differentiation is a free desktop authoring tool, tight integration with Excel and the rest of Microsoft 365, and a licensing on-ramp that scales from a single Pro seat up to enterprise-wide capacity or Fabric licensing.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '1ae91efd-338e-4ef0-9f0b-3f2a51548062';

